1
00:00:02,220 --> 00:00:03,470
I bought a chair.

2
00:00:05,660 --> 00:00:08,469
My room is small, so I got a folding one.

3
00:00:08,470 --> 00:00:09,440
(Episode 9: Sheltering from
the Rain and Huddling Close)

4
00:00:09,441 --> 00:00:12,119
The first person to
sit in this chair was...

5
00:00:12,120 --> 00:00:13,120
Phew...

6
00:00:13,121 --> 00:00:16,000
Tokyo is as crowded as ever.

7
00:00:16,810 --> 00:00:19,080
- I'm exhausted.
- My mom.

8
00:00:23,460 --> 00:00:27,080
This morning, Takako
suddenly said she couldn't drive.

9
00:00:27,300 --> 00:00:30,600
So I had to rush and
call a cab to the bus stop.

10
00:00:30,800 --> 00:00:32,259
Then I had to switch from a bus to a train

11
00:00:32,260 --> 00:00:33,460
just to get here.

12
00:00:34,080 --> 00:00:37,640
At that Shinjuku station, ah...

13
00:00:38,040 --> 00:00:39,449
You know, what's that place called?

14
00:00:39,450 --> 00:00:41,359
The one with all the buses.

15
00:00:41,360 --> 00:00:43,109
- The bus terminal?
- Ah.

16
00:00:43,110 --> 00:00:44,220
Right, right, right.

17
00:00:44,940 --> 00:00:47,180
You have a hospital appointment
at nine tomorrow, right?

18
00:00:47,240 --> 00:00:48,240
I'll go with you.

19
00:00:48,720 --> 00:00:49,220
By the way,

20
00:00:49,221 --> 00:00:52,719
are you sure you can go home the
same day as your cataract surgery?

21
00:00:52,720 --> 00:00:54,560
You don't have to come with me.

22
00:00:55,240 --> 00:00:57,120
I'm staying at Fumi-chan's tonight.

23
00:00:57,150 --> 00:00:59,120
She's going with me tomorrow.

24
00:01:01,820 --> 00:01:05,380
Oh, how's Kuji-san?

25
00:01:06,780 --> 00:01:07,780
Ah...

26
00:01:08,500 --> 00:01:09,500
Yeah.

27
00:01:09,860 --> 00:01:11,900
He's doing well.

28
00:01:14,440 --> 00:01:15,440
You know,

29
00:01:15,700 --> 00:01:17,740
I've always wanted to be with you.

30
00:01:18,460 --> 00:01:19,460
With you, Kuji.

31
00:01:21,180 --> 00:01:25,560
Nothing much has changed since that day.

32
00:01:27,980 --> 00:01:30,020
Our heartbeats pound together,

33
00:01:30,390 --> 00:01:32,520
making it impossible
to tell whose is whose.

34
00:01:34,780 --> 00:01:39,090
It's as if our bodies have become one.

35
00:01:41,580 --> 00:01:42,780
But I also know

36
00:01:44,060 --> 00:01:46,000
that we can never truly merge.

37
00:01:48,080 --> 00:01:49,500
And that alone makes me anxious.

38
00:02:52,200 --> 00:02:57,500
"Life In Smokey Blue"

39
00:02:58,270 --> 00:03:01,740
"The Bouncing Ball and
the Land I Want to See"

40
00:03:05,640 --> 00:03:07,480
What made you decide
to translate it this way?

41
00:03:08,850 --> 00:03:10,420
Since it's a children's book,

42
00:03:10,590 --> 00:03:11,619
I thought it would be good
to use engaging words

43
00:03:11,620 --> 00:03:14,560
to convey how fun the story is.

44
00:03:14,660 --> 00:03:18,260
So for you, Azuma-san,
this was a bit of a departure?

45
00:03:18,600 --> 00:03:19,600
Yes.

46
00:03:20,520 --> 00:03:23,000
While your past translations
have tended to be stiff

47
00:03:23,030 --> 00:03:24,340
due to their precision,

48
00:03:24,440 --> 00:03:26,620
they're gradually starting to change.

49
00:03:27,860 --> 00:03:29,140
Thank you.

50
00:03:30,580 --> 00:03:31,780
Oh, right.

51
00:03:32,080 --> 00:03:33,540
There's also this.

52
00:03:37,020 --> 00:03:38,220
A translation competition...

53
00:03:39,880 --> 00:03:41,650
Competitions can be a matter of luck,

54
00:03:41,880 --> 00:03:42,899
but there's no harm in trying.

55
00:03:42,900 --> 00:03:44,100
That's what I think.

56
00:03:46,280 --> 00:03:47,280
What should I do?

57
00:03:47,281 --> 00:03:48,560
Should I enter?

58
00:03:52,430 --> 00:03:53,630
Delicious!

59
00:03:54,500 --> 00:03:55,700
This must have been expensive.

60
00:03:56,170 --> 00:03:57,880
It was half-off.

61
00:03:57,960 --> 00:03:59,019
It's okay to splurge every
once in a while, right?

62
00:03:59,020 --> 00:04:01,060
It is from a department
store food hall, after all.

63
00:04:03,040 --> 00:04:04,479
Did something happen?

64
00:04:04,480 --> 00:04:05,570
Hm?

65
00:04:06,500 --> 00:04:07,500
No, it's just...

66
00:04:07,900 --> 00:04:09,000
You seem really happy.

67
00:04:10,180 --> 00:04:12,660
I can't hide anything
from you, Shizuka-chan.

68
00:04:13,720 --> 00:04:14,720
Want to hear about it?

69
00:04:15,820 --> 00:04:18,020
- Not really.
- Come on, let me tell you.

70
00:04:20,760 --> 00:04:21,820
Okay, okay.

71
00:04:22,290 --> 00:04:23,290
Today...

72
00:04:23,700 --> 00:04:26,580
my teacher said my
translation style has changed.

73
00:04:26,960 --> 00:04:28,500
That it's not so stiff anymore.

74
00:04:28,900 --> 00:04:29,930
Oh.

75
00:04:30,340 --> 00:04:32,060
- That's great.
- Yeah.

76
00:04:32,480 --> 00:04:34,550
Then Hara-san and I were talking

77
00:04:34,750 --> 00:04:37,710
about entering a translation
competition together.

78
00:04:38,400 --> 00:04:39,910
It's just a small one,

79
00:04:40,280 --> 00:04:42,230
but since you took on that essay job, Kuji,

80
00:04:42,330 --> 00:04:44,410
I thought I'd give it a try too.

81
00:04:47,880 --> 00:04:48,880
Ah.

82
00:04:49,120 --> 00:04:50,120
Sauce.

83
00:04:55,290 --> 00:04:56,290
Oh.

84
00:04:56,300 --> 00:04:57,300
Beef bourguignon?

85
00:04:58,040 --> 00:04:59,680
Wait, isn't this from the Imperial Hotel?

86
00:05:00,720 --> 00:05:02,760
Nukita-san brought it by earlier.

87
00:05:03,140 --> 00:05:06,019
He came to check on
the progress of the essay.

88
00:05:06,020 --> 00:05:07,020
Wow.

89
00:05:08,040 --> 00:05:09,040
What a cool guy.

90
00:05:09,770 --> 00:05:11,640
It used to be my father's favorite.

91
00:05:14,980 --> 00:05:16,180
How's the essay coming along?

92
00:05:19,020 --> 00:05:20,650
I haven't made any progress at all.

93
00:05:22,420 --> 00:05:23,420
I see.

94
00:05:28,800 --> 00:05:29,800
Today,

95
00:05:31,140 --> 00:05:32,760
I went to see Mikami-san.

96
00:05:34,660 --> 00:05:35,920
Yeah.

97
00:05:38,020 --> 00:05:39,020
Mikami-san...

98
00:05:39,640 --> 00:05:41,320
it seems she's moving into a nursing home.

99
00:05:42,400 --> 00:05:43,540
And so...

100
00:05:45,880 --> 00:05:47,180
Once you're all settled in,

101
00:05:47,240 --> 00:05:49,880
please let me come visit
you at the nursing home.

102
00:05:53,120 --> 00:05:54,220
Shizuka-san,

103
00:05:55,340 --> 00:05:58,000
I'm afraid I must decline.

104
00:05:59,720 --> 00:06:00,720
Huh?

105
00:06:01,460 --> 00:06:04,300
I'm very grateful for your
kindness, Shizuka-san.

106
00:06:05,060 --> 00:06:06,060
But...

107
00:06:06,960 --> 00:06:16,040
I want to forever remain in your memory
as Mikami-san the housekeeper.

108
00:06:18,650 --> 00:06:19,750
I see.

109
00:06:20,610 --> 00:06:23,480
That's her way of being
considerate, I guess.

110
00:06:23,910 --> 00:06:25,010
Yeah.

111
00:06:28,220 --> 00:06:29,450
It feels a little lonely,

112
00:06:32,250 --> 00:06:34,520
but at the same time,
I'm also a bit relieved.

113
00:06:39,510 --> 00:06:41,250
It was the same when my father passed away.

114
00:06:43,350 --> 00:06:46,740
I feel like when I'm
trying to write this essay,

115
00:06:48,070 --> 00:06:51,970
the weak and heartless side of me
is being brutally exposed.

116
00:06:56,670 --> 00:06:58,070
It's ready.

117
00:07:00,310 --> 00:07:01,620
Thanks.

118
00:07:02,410 --> 00:07:04,590
- Here, this is for you.
- Hm?

119
00:07:06,690 --> 00:07:07,690
What's this?

120
00:07:08,020 --> 00:07:09,020
Tamaki...

121
00:07:09,250 --> 00:07:11,460
He said he wanted to
borrow an interesting book.

122
00:07:13,010 --> 00:07:14,500
Thanks, I'll give it to him.

123
00:07:19,250 --> 00:07:21,789
Are you eating properly?

124
00:07:21,790 --> 00:07:23,070
How old do you think I am?

125
00:07:23,950 --> 00:07:24,950
Don't worry.

126
00:07:25,010 --> 00:07:28,510
I'm eating well, sleeping well,
and working well.

127
00:07:29,390 --> 00:07:30,590
That's good.

128
00:07:31,830 --> 00:07:33,280
Sis, is everything okay over there?

129
00:07:34,190 --> 00:07:36,570
We're all fine, but...

130
00:07:37,810 --> 00:07:38,810
Mom...

131
00:07:39,610 --> 00:07:42,190
her health hasn't been great lately.

132
00:07:42,490 --> 00:07:44,860
But she seemed so
energetic just the other day.

133
00:07:46,510 --> 00:07:48,140
I guess it's partly her age.

134
00:07:48,800 --> 00:07:50,200
She's become forgetful,

135
00:07:50,230 --> 00:07:52,269
and her movements are a bit unsteady.

136
00:07:52,270 --> 00:07:53,950
So I think she's feeling a little anxious.

137
00:07:54,650 --> 00:07:56,710
I heard she's planning
to get a checkup soon.

138
00:07:59,240 --> 00:08:00,750
I had no idea.

139
00:08:02,370 --> 00:08:06,210
That's because Mom
didn't want to worry you.

140
00:08:09,930 --> 00:08:12,550
Can you keep an eye on her?

141
00:08:12,860 --> 00:08:16,690
Sooner or later, I won't be able to
handle everything on my own.

142
00:08:18,630 --> 00:08:19,630
Yeah.

143
00:08:19,930 --> 00:08:21,260
I understand.

144
00:08:26,390 --> 00:08:29,070
You didn't have to come
all the way from Tokyo.

145
00:08:29,270 --> 00:08:31,210
I had the day off.

146
00:08:32,750 --> 00:08:34,540
How's work at the cram school?

147
00:08:34,810 --> 00:08:36,880
It's... fine.

148
00:08:38,430 --> 00:08:40,330
- Azuma-san, this way please.
- Okay.

149
00:08:40,730 --> 00:08:41,500
Should I take that?
It's okay.

150
00:08:45,050 --> 00:08:48,260
You said you're not feeling
well and are feeling down,

151
00:08:48,290 --> 00:08:51,660
but the tests didn't show anything serious.

152
00:08:52,330 --> 00:08:53,730
I see...

153
00:08:55,550 --> 00:08:57,909
But I get heart palpitations
when I wake up in the morning.

154
00:08:57,910 --> 00:09:01,670
As for feeling down, I suggest
you see a psychosomatic specialist.

155
00:09:02,890 --> 00:09:04,270
Psychosomatic?

156
00:09:07,110 --> 00:09:09,509
- Is that...
- We don't specialize in that field here.

157
00:09:09,510 --> 00:09:12,110
We can do an MRI or other tests,

158
00:09:12,650 --> 00:09:15,080
but we can't diagnose symptoms like these.

159
00:09:16,320 --> 00:09:17,550
So, do I need the tests?

160
00:09:18,250 --> 00:09:19,990
That's up to you.

161
00:09:21,070 --> 00:09:22,490
Up to me...

162
00:09:25,990 --> 00:09:27,510
Then what am I supposed to do?

163
00:09:28,350 --> 00:09:30,990
Like I said, it's your decision.

164
00:09:32,890 --> 00:09:34,309
Um, I...

165
00:09:34,310 --> 00:09:35,510
Then we won't.

166
00:09:36,570 --> 00:09:39,240
- We're not getting treated here.
- Huh?

167
00:09:40,370 --> 00:09:41,370
Mom...

168
00:09:41,570 --> 00:09:43,789
- Let's go home.
- Doctor...

169
00:09:43,790 --> 00:09:44,790
Mom.

170
00:09:45,810 --> 00:09:46,820
Let's go.

171
00:09:49,950 --> 00:09:52,589
Sorry for cutting the
appointment short like that.

172
00:09:52,590 --> 00:09:53,590
Don't be.

173
00:09:54,270 --> 00:09:56,670
It's my fault for not being
able to explain myself properly.

174
00:09:57,470 --> 00:10:00,830
I just caused trouble for
the doctor and for you.

175
00:10:03,410 --> 00:10:05,970
I really hate being like this.

176
00:10:08,590 --> 00:10:09,890
Watch the steps.

177
00:10:11,070 --> 00:10:12,070
Thank you.

178
00:10:30,570 --> 00:10:31,970
You've in your own world.

179
00:10:33,650 --> 00:10:34,650
Oh, be quiet.

180
00:10:35,990 --> 00:10:38,029
How's your mom doing?

181
00:10:38,030 --> 00:10:39,670
You went to the hospital with her, right?

182
00:10:40,089 --> 00:10:41,470
It's a real headache.

183
00:10:43,150 --> 00:10:45,990
That doctor was clearly
impatient with my mom.

184
00:10:47,810 --> 00:10:49,050
No, I actually get it.

185
00:10:49,190 --> 00:10:51,389
We weren't there for a therapy session.

186
00:10:51,390 --> 00:10:53,280
And doctors are only human.

187
00:10:54,570 --> 00:10:55,570
But still...

188
00:10:57,150 --> 00:10:58,789
when I think about my
mom when I'm not around,

189
00:10:58,790 --> 00:11:01,860
I wonder if she's always
been treated like that.

190
00:11:04,870 --> 00:11:08,200
Do you want me to recommend
the hospital my father used to go to?

191
00:11:09,570 --> 00:11:11,370
I know the director there pretty well.

192
00:11:11,970 --> 00:11:13,470
It's a bit far, in the city,

193
00:11:13,500 --> 00:11:14,980
but I think they'll be more thorough.

194
00:11:16,130 --> 00:11:17,130
Hmm...

195
00:11:18,210 --> 00:11:22,880
Thanks, but I'll keep looking for a
hospital that's easier for my mom to get to.

196
00:11:24,270 --> 00:11:25,489
The doctors there are great.

197
00:11:25,490 --> 00:11:26,549
The staff is very kind.

198
00:11:26,550 --> 00:11:27,570
The care is excellent.

199
00:11:28,290 --> 00:11:29,790
- I'm sure your mom would...
- Kuji.

200
00:11:32,910 --> 00:11:34,339
Do you really think

201
00:11:34,340 --> 00:11:35,990
just any old woman

202
00:11:36,020 --> 00:11:39,430
would get the same treatment as
'Kuji Yoshiharu' wherever she goes?

203
00:11:42,930 --> 00:11:43,930
That's not...

204
00:11:44,070 --> 00:11:45,070
Thank you

205
00:11:45,630 --> 00:11:47,700
for being so thoughtful about my mom.

206
00:11:56,490 --> 00:12:00,829
For now, I need to focus on
preparing for the translation competition.

207
00:12:00,830 --> 00:12:02,690
- Azuma, I'm sorry.
- It's okay.

208
00:12:02,950 --> 00:12:04,490
I know you meant well.

209
00:12:05,020 --> 00:12:06,409
Let me give you a ride.

210
00:12:06,410 --> 00:12:08,170
No, really, I'm fine.

211
00:12:09,490 --> 00:12:12,490
Good luck with your essay.

212
00:12:17,027 --> 00:12:19,353
[He's looking up hospital reviews,
specifically related to psychiatry]

213
00:12:19,520 --> 00:12:20,520
Sensei.

214
00:12:21,080 --> 00:12:22,560
There's something I don't understand.

215
00:12:23,800 --> 00:12:24,940
What is it?

216
00:12:25,780 --> 00:12:26,780
Right here.

217
00:12:37,690 --> 00:12:39,089
Sensei, is something wrong?

218
00:12:39,090 --> 00:12:39,960
Hmm?

219
00:12:39,990 --> 00:12:41,300
You seem a little down.

220
00:12:42,120 --> 00:12:43,320
I'm perfectly fine.

221
00:12:43,500 --> 00:12:45,460
I was just lost in thought.

222
00:12:47,760 --> 00:12:49,000
Oh, good.

223
00:12:50,900 --> 00:12:52,770
You're so considerate, Takechi.

224
00:12:55,340 --> 00:12:58,619
Now you just need to master the grammar,
and you'll be perfect.

225
00:12:58,620 --> 00:13:00,680
I have no idea what you're talking about.

226
00:13:01,330 --> 00:13:04,280
Oh, this question...
It looks like it might be right...

227
00:13:19,880 --> 00:13:25,200
I always used to think
I would never become like my father.

228
00:13:29,640 --> 00:13:32,340
As a scholar and a translator,

229
00:13:32,370 --> 00:13:33,880
I respect him.

230
00:13:35,300 --> 00:13:38,210
But I never admired
his arrogant personality.

231
00:13:40,880 --> 00:13:43,020
I thought I was different from my father.

232
00:13:47,120 --> 00:13:48,320
I've always believed that.

233
00:13:48,880 --> 00:13:50,559
Do you really think just any old woman

234
00:13:50,560 --> 00:13:55,530
would get the same treatment as
'Kuji Yoshiharu' wherever she goes?

235
00:13:56,060 --> 00:13:57,200
Azuma, I'm sorry.

236
00:14:11,100 --> 00:14:12,840
Ma'am, are you alright?

237
00:14:15,200 --> 00:14:16,750
Take your time. It's okay.

238
00:14:29,780 --> 00:14:32,430
Well, you caught me in a cool moment.

239
00:14:32,770 --> 00:14:34,880
Yeah, that was really cool.

240
00:14:36,380 --> 00:14:39,440
I just did what anyone would do.

241
00:14:40,520 --> 00:14:42,639
How's studying for your
entrance exams going?

242
00:14:42,640 --> 00:14:43,710
Is it going well?

243
00:14:44,800 --> 00:14:45,800
Yeah.

244
00:14:46,460 --> 00:14:48,880
It's going okay, I guess.

245
00:14:50,360 --> 00:14:51,030
You know,

246
00:14:51,031 --> 00:14:55,090
I want to be a cool adult
like Kuji-san and Saku-chan.

247
00:14:55,540 --> 00:14:57,530
I'm honored that you'd say that.

248
00:15:00,500 --> 00:15:02,730
But I'm not that cool, really.

249
00:15:03,660 --> 00:15:04,490
Huh?

250
00:15:04,491 --> 00:15:05,600
Really?

251
00:15:06,580 --> 00:15:09,970
I think being a translator is super cool.

252
00:15:11,500 --> 00:15:12,940
It must be a tough job, right?

253
00:15:13,880 --> 00:15:15,540
It's not so much that it's tough...

254
00:15:17,420 --> 00:15:18,510
Well...

255
00:15:24,360 --> 00:15:26,000
In the field of medical translation,

256
00:15:28,120 --> 00:15:30,800
there's something called an
'informed assent form' for children.

257
00:15:31,860 --> 00:15:35,759
It's a document given to children when
they're invited to participate in trials

258
00:15:35,760 --> 00:15:38,580
to test a drug's effectiveness and safety.

259
00:15:41,640 --> 00:15:44,800
While you're trying to figure out how
to translate it so a child can understand,

260
00:15:44,840 --> 00:15:47,380
you also think about the
children who are battling illnesses.

261
00:15:49,340 --> 00:15:50,540
And it just breaks your heart.

262
00:15:59,440 --> 00:16:01,560
Behind the words are real people.

263
00:16:03,780 --> 00:16:05,630
With their own lives.

264
00:16:08,760 --> 00:16:11,400
I always remind myself
never to forget that.

265
00:16:14,180 --> 00:16:15,270
That's so cool.

266
00:16:16,820 --> 00:16:18,510
Kuji-san, you really are the coolest.

267
00:16:21,600 --> 00:16:25,650
So, Tamaki, what kind of
adult do you want to be?

268
00:16:27,240 --> 00:16:28,240
Oh...

269
00:16:31,800 --> 00:16:33,680
My mom once told me

270
00:16:34,920 --> 00:16:36,120
the meaning behind my name.

271
00:16:37,600 --> 00:16:40,400
The character for 'Tamaki'
means 'ring' or 'circle'.

272
00:16:42,420 --> 00:16:45,700
It means 'a circle that connects people'.

273
00:16:47,000 --> 00:16:48,000
I see.

274
00:16:51,780 --> 00:16:53,540
I hope I can become someone like that.

275
00:17:00,420 --> 00:17:01,720
You're pretty cool too, Tamaki.

276
00:17:02,480 --> 00:17:03,150
Huh?

277
00:17:03,220 --> 00:17:04,390
You think so?

278
00:17:06,720 --> 00:17:08,280
Oh, shoot.
I have to get to cram school.

279
00:17:12,140 --> 00:17:13,140
Oh.

280
00:17:13,980 --> 00:17:14,980
This is...

281
00:17:15,300 --> 00:17:19,130
I've been reading it lately. I heard
Saku-chan read it in middle school too.

282
00:17:26,580 --> 00:17:28,580
I got the dried sweet potatoes.

283
00:17:29,500 --> 00:17:31,360
They're delicious.

284
00:17:31,840 --> 00:17:33,680
Could you give them to Kuji-san for me?

285
00:17:33,960 --> 00:17:34,960
Sure.

286
00:17:36,820 --> 00:17:38,020
And...

287
00:17:38,920 --> 00:17:42,990
I found a new hospital for you.
We can go check it out together.

288
00:17:43,460 --> 00:17:44,460
Oh.

289
00:17:45,040 --> 00:17:47,479
That's all taken care of.

290
00:17:47,480 --> 00:17:48,919
What?

291
00:17:48,920 --> 00:17:52,470
My neighbor recommended
some herbal medicine.

292
00:17:53,760 --> 00:17:56,710
I've been drinking it,
and I feel much better.

293
00:17:57,400 --> 00:17:59,270
You could have told me.

294
00:17:59,900 --> 00:18:01,810
I was so worried.

295
00:18:02,240 --> 00:18:03,940
Sorry, sorry.

296
00:18:07,000 --> 00:18:10,450
Well, I'm just glad you're okay.

297
00:18:11,880 --> 00:18:13,836
We were just talking about
how, when it gets a little warmer,

298
00:18:13,860 --> 00:18:17,360
we're going to go to the rose
garden with the neighbors.

299
00:18:18,460 --> 00:18:22,060
Mom, you seem happy.

300
00:18:22,380 --> 00:18:25,040
I am. I'm very happy.

301
00:18:27,060 --> 00:18:28,060
What about you?

302
00:18:29,000 --> 00:18:30,010
Are you happy?

303
00:18:31,540 --> 00:18:34,410
Yeah, I am.

304
00:18:35,900 --> 00:18:38,900
(Hoshi no Monogatari
Translation Competition Office)

305
00:18:42,030 --> 00:18:43,030
Please...!

306
00:18:52,483 --> 00:18:55,476
[Kuji is working on a draft
of the essay about his father]

307
00:19:06,910 --> 00:19:07,910
Yes.

308
00:19:10,430 --> 00:19:11,430
Yes.

309
00:19:11,930 --> 00:19:13,450
I've finally started writing.

310
00:19:15,590 --> 00:19:16,620
Okay.

311
00:19:19,010 --> 00:19:20,010
Okay.

312
00:19:23,630 --> 00:19:24,630
Huh?

313
00:19:28,800 --> 00:19:29,800
(Sakutaro: Working from home all day?)
(Kuji Shizuka: Yep.)
(Sakutaro: If it's on my way
back, I was thinking of stopping by.)

314
00:19:30,601 --> 00:19:32,206
(Kuji Shizuka: Roger that.) (Sakutaro: I
submitted my entry for the competition.)

315
00:19:32,230 --> 00:19:33,940
Oh, Azuma-san.

316
00:19:36,350 --> 00:19:38,459
We both made the deadline
for the translation competition.

317
00:19:38,460 --> 00:19:39,210
That's great, isn't it?
It really is.

318
00:19:41,470 --> 00:19:46,470
I actually pulled an all-nighter at the
last minute and redid the whole thing.

319
00:19:48,670 --> 00:19:50,290
Did something happen?

320
00:19:52,850 --> 00:19:55,360
Well... Kuji and I...

321
00:19:55,790 --> 00:19:56,990
Azuma.

322
00:19:58,950 --> 00:20:01,630
Azuma... Sakutaro!

323
00:20:02,490 --> 00:20:03,490
Huh?

324
00:20:03,550 --> 00:20:04,790
Kuji?

325
00:20:06,090 --> 00:20:07,270
Let's go right now.

326
00:20:07,510 --> 00:20:08,510
To the hot springs.

327
00:20:09,650 --> 00:20:10,670
What?!

328
00:20:11,470 --> 00:20:12,470
Hot springs.

329
00:20:13,690 --> 00:20:14,890
I even booked us a room.

330
00:20:18,550 --> 00:20:20,080
Are you serious, Kuji?

331
00:20:20,970 --> 00:20:22,070
You're the best!

332
00:20:36,230 --> 00:20:40,240
Ah, this is amazing.

333
00:20:41,000 --> 00:20:42,840
This is pure bliss. It's heaven.

334
00:20:43,930 --> 00:20:45,770
I didn't realize you'd be this happy.

335
00:20:46,870 --> 00:20:48,380
Then we have Nukita-san to thank.

336
00:20:49,830 --> 00:20:50,830
Huh?

337
00:20:51,090 --> 00:20:52,550
Nukita-san gave them to me.

338
00:20:52,930 --> 00:20:54,020
These gift certificates.

339
00:20:54,950 --> 00:20:56,830
He said he couldn't
make it at the last minute.

340
00:20:57,610 --> 00:20:58,820
What a cool guy...

341
00:21:01,270 --> 00:21:02,599
By the way,

342
00:21:02,600 --> 00:21:05,530
asking me out on the same
day is pretty sudden, don't you think?

343
00:21:11,370 --> 00:21:12,970
About your mother...

344
00:21:14,910 --> 00:21:15,800
What I said was so insensitive.

345
00:21:15,840 --> 00:21:16,840
I'm truly sorry.

346
00:21:20,450 --> 00:21:22,240
I've been thinking about it ever since.

347
00:21:26,010 --> 00:21:27,580
But I couldn't stand it anymore.

348
00:21:29,030 --> 00:21:30,550
I just really wanted to see you.

349
00:21:33,060 --> 00:21:36,430
Shizuka-chan, it's rare
to see you so honest.

350
00:21:42,130 --> 00:21:43,130
Asimov.

351
00:21:44,150 --> 00:21:45,150
Hmm?

352
00:21:45,870 --> 00:21:47,950
I heard it from Tamaki
when I saw him the other day.

353
00:21:50,310 --> 00:21:52,739
That Asimov book you used to read,

354
00:21:52,740 --> 00:21:54,810
Tamaki is reading it now.

355
00:21:55,890 --> 00:21:56,890
Yeah.

356
00:21:58,610 --> 00:22:01,650
I actually read it in middle school, too.

357
00:22:07,310 --> 00:22:10,290
We're so alike.

358
00:22:48,760 --> 00:22:51,130
I wish we could just
freeze everything about us,

359
00:22:53,010 --> 00:22:56,540
on a winter night like this.

360
00:23:02,080 --> 00:23:04,800
(Final Episode Preview) I wish I
could tell my past self all of this.

361
00:23:05,430 --> 00:23:07,210
I've gotten to you.

362
00:23:07,220 --> 00:23:09,550
There are good days and bad days.

363
00:23:09,630 --> 00:23:11,070
That's just how life is.

364
00:23:11,250 --> 00:23:12,890
I don't want to go back.

365
00:23:13,060 --> 00:23:14,560
Want to stay another night?

